  "notes": "Komi-Permyak (перем коми / коми-пермяцкӧй кыв) of Perm Krai, Russia — the second Permic literary standard alongside Komi-Zyrian. INPUT CONTRACT: modern Komi-Permyak Cyrillic text, Unicode NFC. Orthography (1938): all the Russian letters plus ⟨І і⟩ and ⟨Ӧ ӧ⟩, i.e. the same alphabet as Komi-Zyrian, and the two standards are described as sharing the same 26 native consonants and 7 vowels (i ɨ u e ə o a); ⟨ц ф х⟩ occur essentially only in Russian loanwords. The grapheme map is therefore the Komi-Zyrian one: ⟨д з л н с т⟩ → /ɟ ʑ ʎ ɲ ɕ c/ before ⟨е ё и ю я ь⟩ (entered as multigraph keys so maximal munch prefers them), ⟨і⟩ = 'hard i' /i/ leaving the preceding consonant hard, and the affricate digraphs ⟨дж⟩ /dʒ/, ⟨дз⟩ /dʑ/, ⟨тш⟩ /tʃ/. Iotated ⟨е ё ю я⟩ list the plain vowel first, the [j]-initial reading (word-initial / post-vocalic) second. Dialect-level differences from Komi-Zyrian are lexical and phonetic rather than orthographic and are not modelled. The historic Molodtsov alphabet is out of scope.",
